<br>
Also please keep in mind that while a Shaman or a Druid can pretty much do all the 'utility' stuff that a Paladin can, a Warrior can't.<br>
<br>
If a Paladin takes our slot, we have no secondary attractiveness that will gain us a spot.  They won't invite us for our snare, our root, our stun, our secondary heals, our anything, because it doesn't exist.  If a Warrior is tanking for a group there is still room for a Shadow Knight or Paladin if a Druid, Shamen, etc aren't available.<br>
<br>
You usually want a snarer, right?  Shadow Knight, Wizard, Druid, Necro, or Ranger.<br>
<br>
You usually need a priest, right?  Shamen, Druid, Cleric, or in a pinch a Paladin (primarily at high levels).<br>
<br>
You might need an evacer, right?  Wizard or Druid.<br>
<br>
You need damage dealers, right?  Monk, Rogue, Wizard, are the best choices.  Then Mage, Necro, Druid, Warrior, Beastlord, Paladin, Shadow Knight.  Neither the Knights nor the Warrior are really going to shine in the damage dealing department.  Second choices at best.<br>
<br>
You need a tank, right?  Warrior, Monk, Paladin, Shadow Knight.<br>
<br>
See we don't really have any additional functionality that will remotely make us attractive for a group if we aren't tanking.  If the tank spot is taken, there are MUCH better choices for damage dealers.  Neither the Knight nor the Warrior are going to be anyone's first choice.  If no other damage dealers are available they might take a Warrior over a Knight, but it rarely comes down to that, does it?<br>
<br>
If we can't at least shine in the tank spot, you basically are saying that where ever a Paladin or Shadow Knight is tanking, a Warrior isn't needed.  It also means the where ever a Warrior is tanking a Paladin or Shadow Knight MAY be needed if some other class isn't filling the utility spot.<br>
<br>
